## How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK supports **two injection styles**:

### 1. Constructor injection (non-static class) — preferred for services

```
[McpServerToolType]
public class MyTools(HttpClient http, ILogger<MyTools> logger) { ... }
```

The class is resolved from the DI container each time a tool is called. Services like `HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, or your own interfaces are injected via the constructor. Register them in `Program.cs` (`AddHttpClient()`, `AddSingleton<T>()`, etc.).

### 2. Method parameter injection (static class)

```
[McpServerTool]
public static async Task<string> Fetch(
    string id,                    // ← exposed in tool schema
    HttpClient httpClient,        // ← injected by DI, hidden from schema
    CancellationToken ct)         // ← injected, hidden from schema
```

DI services appear as regular parameters. The SDK distinguishes them from tool arguments automatically — **DI-resolved types and `CancellationToken` never appear in the tool's JSON schema**.

### Key DI rules

| Registered in DI? | Has `[Description]`? | Result |
|---|---|---|
| No | Yes | Tool parameter (shown to LLM) |
| Yes | No | Injected by DI (hidden) |
| — | — | `CancellationToken`, `IMcpServer`, `IProgress<>` are always injected |

The `.WithToolsFromAssembly()` call uses reflection to find all `[McpServerToolType]` classes at startup, wiring DI automatically. For **Native AOT**, use `.WithTools<WeatherTools>()` instead.
